{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17645878","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17645878"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:22:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:22:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18139"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18139"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.06,0.12,0.45,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10853"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107750"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10853","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10853"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18139"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90182"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7231"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25250"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25253"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39824"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39826"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107750"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe radial nerve is a major peripheral nerve of the upper limb. It has both motor and sensory functions. The superficial branch of the radial nerve is primarily responsible for sensory innervation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the sensory distribution of the superficial branch of the radial nerve?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dorsal aspect of the lateral 2.5 digits, excluding nail beds","Dorsal aspect of the lateral 2.5 digits, including nail beds","Dorsal aspect of the lateral 4 digits, excluding nail beds","Dorsal aspect of the lateral 3.5 digits, excluding nail beds","Dorsal aspect of the lateral 3.5 digits, including nail beds"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe superficial branch of the radial nerve provides sensory innervation to the \u003Cstrong\u003Edorsal aspect of the lateral 3.5 digits, excluding nail beds\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis is clinically relevant because sensory loss in this distribution can help localise lesions of the radial nerve, such as in wrist drop or nerve injury following humeral fractures.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The superficial branch of the radial nerve supplies sensory innervation to the dorsal aspect of the lateral 3.5 digits, excluding the nail beds.","The nail beds of the fingers are innervated by the median and ulnar nerves, not the radial nerve."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Glover NM, Black AC, Murphy PB. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Radial Nerve. [Updated 2023 Nov 5]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534840/","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Raszewski JA, Black AC, Launico MV, et al. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Hand Compartments. [Updated 2023 Oct 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/books/NBK532942/","